# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-monaco
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-monaco/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The Dodge lineup was refreshed for the 1958 model year, continuing the three-line scheme of the 1955 Dodges with the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer was added as a new top-of-the-line model in spring.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The 1958 Dodges shared their basic mechanicals with the De Soto, but featured special styling.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The Coronet lasted through the 1959 model years.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 with 123 hp (92 kW), but the 325 in3 (5.3 L) *Red Ram (2bbl)/Super Red Ram (4bbl)* V8 was an option.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Coronets may typically be identified by a script mounted at the trailing edge of the belt-line stainless steel trim strip and a plain "up-sweep" molding of the rear fin trim, where both Royal and Custom Royal had a "dipping" element to the up-sweep trim.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were painted with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were club sedan, sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Lancers were further identified by a lance and shield emblem on each fin.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), and four-door hardtop (Lancer).
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] It came with the 350 in3 (5.7 L) Ram Fire V8 with a standard two-barrel carburetor, but the optional four-barrel carburetor delivered 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] A feature of the Custom Royal was its bumper-mounted exhaust ports which were only available on the Royal and Coronet models as part of the D-500 options.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Identifying exterior characteristics include Custom Royal script at the trailing edge of the belt-line molding, the pronounced check-mark, gold anodized Dodge block letters on the hood, and gold anodized Dodge script on the passenger side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized and had a unique rectangular pattern.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] All Custom Royals included a stainless molding above the bumper, on the flat edge below the trunk opening.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] To combat the recession of 1958, the Chrysler Corporation developed a program of spring specials to present a mid-year trim change on most of its makes.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The factory-produced spring specials for Dodge included a new wide, full-length belt line molding, grille emblem, fin end-caps, and a wide license plate escutcheon.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The Chrysler Corporation also shipped out all of these trim items individually to dealers so the dealers could "freshen up" the cars sitting on their lots.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Dealer-installed spring specials often include some elements of the factory spring special trim, but not always all.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] New exterior colors introduced for spring were Poppy Red, Frosted Turquoise, and Paris Rose.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Unrelated to spring specials, Dodge changed the headlight trim midway through the production run.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Later cars have a wide lower edge to the headlight trim while early cars have a thin lower edge.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Trying to boost sales, the **Regal Lancer** model was added in February and only available as a two-door hardtop with special colors, exterior trim and interior.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Four color combinations were available: bronze with white trim, bronze with black trim, black with bronze trim, and white with bronze trim.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] It featured special nameplates at the front of the side spear trim and heavy eyebrow trim.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Inside, Regal Lancers got their own interior with unique trim and door panels featuring molded armrests.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] A bronze instrument panel with textured aluminum inserts was a Regal Lancer exclusive.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The standard engine offered for Regal Lancers was the 350 cubic inch displacement "Ram Fire" V8.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Optional engine choices were the 361 cubic inch displacement **D-500** and **Super D-500** iterations.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The Suburban was Dodge's two-door station wagon in 1958.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] All station wagons came standard with the 350 Ram Fire engine.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The entry level four-door station wagon in 1958 was the Sierra.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Sierras came in either the six-passenger seat configuration or the nine-passenger "Spectator" seat configuration.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] From the exterior the nine-passenger configuration can be easily identified by the spare tire panel behind the rear wheel opening and the rubber step-spots on the rear bumper.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Custom Sierra wagons were the top-of-the-line station wagon offering for Dodge.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] As with Sierras, they were available as either six-passenger or Spectators.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The D-500 engine option was available across all models and all body styles including station wagons and the Regal Lancer.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The D-500 family of engines includes a four-barrel option, a dual four-barrel (Super D-500), and a Bendix electronic fuel injection system for the Super D-500.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The Bendix E.F.I. system proved to be troublesome and what few examples were built were recalled to be fitted with the normally aspirated dual four-barrel carburetor system.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] On passenger cars, the D-500 emblem was located on the driver side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] On station wagons, the D-500 emblem was located below the tail gate latch.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The 1958 D-500 emblem was unique to that year.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] All D-500s came with bumper mounted exhaust ports.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The California Highway patrol was so impressed with the performance of the new Dodge they ordered 200 vehicles with the D-500 option to be used on patrol duty.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] This was Chrysler's first move into specialized Police cars, and its success paved the way for decades of special police packages.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Dodge also offered a D-500-1 that was strictly for racing.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] It set several speed records on the sand at Daytona and the salt flats at Bonneville.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] They were also designed for NASCAR and drag racing.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The D-500-1 package was only available in a Coronet hardtop, convertible or two-door sedan with a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] Apart from the spring specials, Dodge offered a variety of paint and trim schemes for 1958.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The monotone, basic, and deluxe two-tones all used the "short" belt-line trim with model script behind the trailing edge.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The saddle two-tone used the 1957 full-length belt-line trim and placed the model script below the front fender belt-line trim.
[src:dodge-monaco/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer had paint and trim unique to that model.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:dodge-monaco/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The **Ambassador** is an automobile manufactured and marketed by American Motors Corporation (AMC) from model year 1957 through 1974.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Over its eight generations, Ambassadors were available in two- and four-door sedans, two- and four-door hardtops, four-door station wagons, and two-door convertibles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The cars were classified as a full-size car from 1957 through 1961, a mid-size from 1962 until 1966, and again as a full-size car from 1967 through 1974.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador was positioned at the top as the flagship line for the automaker, featuring more standard equipment, higher levels of trim, or increased size.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] When discontinued, the *Ambassador* nameplate was in use from 1927 until 1974, making it the longest continuously used car nameplate until then.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Initially referring to a top trim level between 1927 and 1931, Nash used the *Ambassador* nameplate for their premium models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ambassadors were manufactured at AMC's Lake Front plant in Kenosha, Wisconsin, until 1974, and at AMC's Brampton Assembly in Ontario, Canada, between 1963 and 1966.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Australian Motor Industries (AMI) assembled Ambassadors from knock-down kits with right-hand drive from 1961 until 1963.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The U.S. fifth-generation Ambassadors were manufactured by Industrias Kaiser Argentina (IKA) in Córdoba, Argentina, from 1965 until 1972, and assembled by ECASA in Costa Rica from 1965 through 1970.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Planta REO assembled the first-generation Ambassadors in Mexico at its Monterrey, Nuevo León plant.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Fifth- and seventh-generation Ambassadors were modified into custom stretch limousines in Argentina and the U.S.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador nameplate, boasting one of the longest continuous runs in American automotive history, originated with Nash Motors in the late 1920s. and was a consistent symbol of luxury, prestige, and advanced engineering for decades.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The first application of the Ambassador name by Nash Motors occurred during the 1927 model year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Initially, it was introduced not as a standalone model, but as a high-trim designation for a specially appointed four-door, five-passenger sedan.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This established the Ambassador as a top-tier offering, signifying a heightened level of equipment, comfort, and refinement within Nash's burgeoning lineup.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] By 1932, the Ambassador nameplate had evolved into its distinct model range and its position as the flagship and top-of-the-line offering in the Nash lineup.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Throughout the pre-war years, the Nash Ambassador became renowned for its lavish equipment, robust construction, and high quality, earning it the nickname of "the Kenosha Duesenberg" — a nod to its Wisconsin manufacturing home and the car's opulent nature.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Competition for the Ambassador during the 1930s included Packard, Lincoln, and the Duesenberg.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] These are "Approved Classics" by the Classic Car Club of America (CCCA).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The nameplate was later applied to the marque's top-of-the-line models, symbolizing prestige and advanced engineering.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador served as a platform for technological advancements, such as unibody construction (as Nash termed it, "Unitized Body"), and it was among the first popular domestic automobiles to feature this advanced structural design, laying the crucial groundwork for modern automotive engineering.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Following World War II, the Ambassador continued as Nash's premier offering, undergoing significant redesigns, including the distinctive aerodynamic "Airflyte" styling.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Nash Ambassador was first with standard stacked quad headlamps.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] At the time, a design that violated some state laws regarding headlights, but a feature that later became popular on many cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] After the 1954 merger of Nash-Kelvinator and Hudson Motors to form American Motors Corporation, the Nash Ambassador continued to be produced under the Nash brand and dealer system, maintaining its identity within the newly formed company.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The unexpected death of AMC's visionary founder and CEO, George W.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Mason, in October 1954, marked a pivotal transition for the nascent corporation.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] George Romney, whom Mason had been grooming as his successor, ascended to president and CEO.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] He inherited a company facing stiff competition from the domestic "Big Three" (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Romney recognized that success in the postwar marketplace demanded substantial sales volumes to amortize the prohibitively high vehicle tooling and production costs.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] He declared that "competing with the 'Big Three' was the road to disaster" and that "the only way to compete against Detroit's Big Three was to beat them at their own game.".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Romney's primary strategic pivot was to concentrate AMC's efforts on the compact-car market segment, with its highly successful Rambler models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This segment was a strategic niche where the dominant domestic automakers had not yet introduced dedicated compact offerings, giving AMC a crucial competitive advantage.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Despite this new focus, the Nash Ambassador, a legacy of the pre-merger Nash Motors, continued to be marketed under the new corporate umbrella for a transition from 1954 through 1957.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1954 Nash Ambassador models were largely carryovers from their 1953 predecessors, maintaining the distinctive "Airflyte" styling.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] An innovation was the first American automobile to feature a front-end, fully integrated heating, ventilating, and air-conditioning system.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The marketplace in 1954 was dominated by an intense sales war between Ford and General Motors, which impacted the business of independent automakers like Hudson, Kaiser, Nash, Packard, and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ford and Chevrolet aggressively pushed their standard-size models to dealers, often with deep discounts, leading to declining sales for the independents.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The newly formed AMC saw its compact-sized Rambler models (sold by Nash and Hudson dealers) grow while those of the Ambassador declined, with 21,428 built in 1954.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1955 model year Ambassadors included a facelift under the direction of Edmund E.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Anderson that featured wrap-around windshields and a new oval grille with integrated headlights.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] New front fenders now had wheel arches to expose more of the front wheels and tires.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] For the first time, the Ambassadors were available with a V8 engine supplied by Packard and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador models underwent a significant restyle for 1956.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] A "V-line" theme adorned the cars, featuring a variety of two- and three-tone color schemes.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador lineup was streamlined, offering Nash I6 and a larger V8 engine from Packard.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, AMC introduced its in-house developed 250 cu in (4.1 L) V8 engine in April 1956.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1957 Nash Ambassador models included numerous features and were notable for being among the first cars equipped with "quad" headlights as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] These were distinctively stacked vertically within the front fender "pontoons".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The standard engine for the 1957 Ambassador was AMC's own V8, a modern overhead valve design displacing 327 cu in (5.4 L).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] While Romney championed the compact car strategy, developing a redesigned 1958 Nash Ambassador based on a stretched and re-skinned 1956 Rambler body was underway.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Designers at AMC also crafted a re-trimmed Hudson equivalent, tentatively named the "Rebel," intended for Hudson dealers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, Romney made a difficult but decisive choice as sales of the traditional large-sized Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models continued declining.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Romney essentially "represented a rejection of the standard way of running a U.S. automaker".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] In 1956, he determined that consumer confidence in these historic Nash and Hudson nameplates had waned beyond recovery.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The decision to discontinue two iconic brands came so late that some early promotional materials for the forthcoming 1958 Ambassador even had the Nash and Hudson names airbrushed out.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] After producing fewer than 3,600 large-sized Nash cars in 1957, the final Nash Ambassador rolled off the Kenosha, Wisconsin, production line on 25 June 1957.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This marked the end of the Nash brand, as Romney, believing both Nash and Hudson were no longer relevant, retired both names to focus AMC's resources entirely on the successful Rambler line, which was officially registered as a separate marque for 1957.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1958 Ambassador became a "full-size" compact car in the Rambler model line.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This was a change from the plans to produce a stretched 117-inch (2,972 mm) wheelbase version of the Rambler platform for Nash dealers to be the new Nash Ambassador and another version for Hudson dealers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] During September 1957, just before committing to the production of the new long-wheelbase versions of the Hudson and the Nash, CEO Romney dropped the Nash and Hudson marques.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] With the legacy brands of the predecessor automakers canceled, work on a replacement large car continued, and on 8 October 1957, AMC introduced the 1958 "Ambassador V-8 by Rambler" on a 117-inch (2,972 mm) wheelbase.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The body received a total reskinning with "surfaces stretched taut over an unabashedly square-rigged framework" removing any traces of the previous, Nash derived, roundness or "tubbiness".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Its features included the new 327 cu in (5.4 L) AMC V8 engine mated to a BorgWarner supplied three-speed automatic transmission with push-button gear selection on the dashboard.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The engine featured a four-barrel carburetor and dual exhausts.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This was the hydraulic lifter version of AMC's 327 V8 rated at 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS) and 360 lb⋅ft (488 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Management had found that the public associated the Rambler name with small economy cars and did not want the upscale nature of the new Ambassador to be so closely associated with Rambler's favorable, but economical image.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Therefore, a decision was made that the larger Ambassador would be marketed as the **Ambassador V-8 by Rambler** to identify it with the Rambler name's burgeoning success, but to indicate an air of exclusivity by showing it to be a different kind of vehicle.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, the car wore "Rambler Ambassador" badges on its front fenders.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ambassador body styles for 1958 included a four-door sedan and a hardtop sedan, a four-door pillared station wagon, and a pillarless **Cross Country** station wagon.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This wagon body style was an industry first in the 1956 Nash and Hudson Rambler line, on which all the 1958 Ramblers were based.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Model identification was located on the car's front fenders and deck lid.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] **Super** trim level Ambassadors featured painted side trim that complemented the body color; **Custom** models featured a silver anodized aluminum panel on sedans and vinyl woodgrain decals on station wagons.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1958 Ambassador came equipped with such luxury items as an electric clock, twin front and rear ashtrays, Nash's traditional "deep coil" spring suspension front and rear, split-back reclining front seats that fold down into a bed, as well as upscale fabrics for the interior.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Numerous safety features (such as deep-dished steering wheels and padded dashboards) came standard, while lap seat belts were optional.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1958 Ambassador is substantially longer than the 108-inch (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, both lines shared the same basic body, styling, and visual cues.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, the Ambassador's extra nine inches (230 mm) of wheelbase (and, therefore, overall length) were added ahead of the cowl, meaning the passenger compartment had the same volume as the smaller Ramblers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassadors came with plusher interior and exterior trims, while the front end incorporated the Rebel "V-Line" grille from the prototype Hudson model.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Through effective market segmentation, the Ambassador was positioned to compete with the larger models offered by other automakers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] American Motors first produced its V8 in 1956, a modern overhead valve engine displacing 250 cu in (4.1 L), with a 3.25-inch stroke, forged steel crankshaft, which when equipped with a 4-barrel carburetor, was rated at 215 hp (160 kW; 218 PS).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] For 1957, AMC bored the 3+1⁄2-inch 250 CID V8 to 4 inches and 327 cu in (5.4 L) displacement, which, when offered in the Rambler Rebel used solid lifters and Bendix electronic fuel injection, was rated at 288 hp (215 kW; 292 PS).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Although AMC's 327 CID V8 shares its displacement with the Chevrolet small-block, AMC's 327 came out five years before Chevrolet offered its 327 V8.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador had an excellent power-to-weight ratio for its time and provided spirited performance with 0 to 60 mph (0 to 97 km/h) times of less than 10 seconds, with low 17-second times through a quarter-mile (402 m) dragstrip.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] It could be equipped with a limited slip differential, as well as power brakes, power steering, power windows, and air conditioning.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] "The Ambassador was Rambler's economy flagship, and road testers liked the speed, room, luxury features, and engineering integrity".<ref*Willson, Quentin; Selby, David (1995).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The new positioning of the Rambler brand in a larger car line with added features resulted in sales of 14,570 Ambassadors for 1958.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The new model was positioned in the mid-priced class alongside Pontiac and Mercury.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The interiors were nicely appointed interiors and the Ambassador even featured the obligatory for the era tailfins.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, buyers in the mid-priced bracket were not drawn in large numbers to the bigger Rambler.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The recession of 1958 saw a sharp worldwide economic downturn which made mid-model year reintroduction of the compact Nash Rambler, produced from 1950 through 1954, as the "new" 1958 Rambler American an unprecedented comeback and a sales success for AMC during a deteriorating marketplace.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] For 1959, the Ambassador received a revised grille, side trim, and redesigned rear door skins that swept into the tailfins instead of terminating at the C-pillar.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Scotchlite reflectors were also added to the rear of the tailfins to increase visibility at night.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Front and rear bumpers were over 20% thicker and featured recessed center sections to protect license plates.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Adjustable headrests for the front seats were a new option, an industry first.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] AMC touted the added comfort the headrests provided, as well as their potential for reducing whiplash injuries in the event of a rear-end collision.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Other changes included the activation of the starter through the neutral pushbutton (on automatic transmission-equipped cars) and the addition of an optional "Powr-Saver" engine fan, which featured a fluid-filled clutch for quieter high-speed operation.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1959 model year also saw the addition of an optional "Air-Coil Ride" air suspension system, utilizing airbags installed within the rear coil springs.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] An engine-driven compressor, reservoir, and ride-height control valve comprised the rest of the system.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Still, as other automakers discovered, the troublesome nature of air suspension outweighed its benefits.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The option proved unpopular and was discontinued at the end of the model year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ambassador sales improved considerably over 1958, reaching an output of 23,769; nearly half of which were **Custom** four-door sedans.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Less popular was the hardtop station wagon, of which 578 were built.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The decision to discontinue the Nash and Hudson brands resulted in developing the second-generation Rambler Ambassador design.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] It was the only American midsize, luxury high-performance car offered in 1960.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The "Ambassador by Rambler" was marketed by AMC as America's Compact Luxury Car.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1960 model year lineup was reskinned, using new fenders, hood, deck lid, door skins, roofline, grille, taillights, bumpers, windshield, and backlight.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The lower hood line, lower windshield cowl, simplified side trims, and egg-crate grille with stand-up letters spelling AMBASSADOR were significant.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] At the same time, the tailfins were reduced in height and were canted to either side, making for an integrated appearance, and the AMBASSADOR name was repeated across the rear trunk lid.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The overall effect was relatively fresh, as the new roof had a lower, lighter look to complement the lower fins and grille.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The design changes and the new grille provided "a more expensive look".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1960 Ambassador was available only with four doors in sedan and station wagon body types.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The station wagons had two rows of seats for six adult passengers or an additional rear-facing third row for an eight-passenger version.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Additionally, a pillarless sedan (hardtop) and station wagon were available in the top-of-the-line "Custom" trim version.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Three trim levels started with a "Deluxe" sedan reserved for fleet customers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The "Super" was the entry-level consumer version and available only as a pillared sedan and pillared six- or eight-passenger station wagon body styles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The top "Custom" trim models in both pillared or hardtop versions included fender ornaments, a clock, full wheel covers as well as additional padding for the rear seat, dash, and sun visors.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] To enhance the visual length of the cars, a full-length bodyside molding was painted in a contrasting color on the Super trim models or enclosed a brushed aluminum panel on the Ambassador Custom series.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ambassadors now came with a unique compound curved windshield that cut into the roof.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This improved visibility, did away with the "knee knocker" dogleg design of AMC's first-generation wrap-around windshield, and resulted in an even stiffer unitized structure.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1960 Ambassador had a low cowl, providing excellent visibility with the compound windshield.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] All 1960 Ambassadors came with a new instrument cluster under a padded cowl and illuminated controls for lights, wipers, fan, and defrost functions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Additional conveniences included a spotlight on the accelerator pedal and a net above the padded sun visors to hold lightweight items.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The top-of-the-line Ambassador Custom models came standard with individual "airliner" reclining front seats that now had even more luxurious fabrics than in previous years.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] All Ambassadors included the AMC's 327 cu in (5.4 L) V8, but for the first time, it was available in two versions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1960 Ambassadors continued with an independent front suspension with upper and lower A-arms, an enclosed drive shaft (torque tube) with a live rear axle using 4-link trailing arms, and coil springs at all four wheels.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, the suspension was revised, resulting in better handling.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Equipped with the 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS) 327 cu in (5.4 L) V8 and the BorgWarner pushbutton-operated three-speed planetary gear and torque converter automatic transmission, the Ambassadors reached 60 miles per hour (97 km/h) in just over 9 seconds and passed the quarter-mile in 17 seconds.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassadors featured soft springs and a solid build, making them ride silently and smoothly, according to reviewers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The year set a new record for AMC, with total production reaching almost half a million cars and total revenue exceeding $1 billion.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Rambler Six and V8 along with the Rambler American represented almost 95% of AMC's automobile sales.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] A total of 23,798 Ambassadors were built for the 1960 model year, with the Custom sedan being the most popular body and trim version (10,949 units).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Only 302 Deluxe (fleet) sedans were delivered.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1961 Ambassador continued the previous year's 117-inch (2,972 mm) primary unitized platform, but received an unusual new front-end styling that was overseen by AMC's in-house design department headed by Edmund E.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The pillar-less four-door hardtop sedan and station wagon models were no longer available for 1961.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador's new design consisted of a trapezoid grille and headlights that floated in a body-colored panel.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] At the same time, the front fenders arched downward and forward of the leading edge of the hood.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Unlike anything else on the market, AMC's marketing department promoted the look as "European".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The interior featured a "space-age" inspired oval instrument pod, centrally located behind the slender, two-tone steering wheel.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This evocative pod housed the speedometer flanked by temperature and fuel gauges, along with warning lamps, directional indicators, and the odometer, all encased in a dark-padded, color-matched enclosure.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Other innovative elements included the "Handi-Pak Net Carrier" integrated into the fiberglass acoustical headliner as well as the "Airliner" reclining front seats with Airfoam cushions, capable of folding flat to form "Twin Travel Beds".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] While the new look was meant to distinguish the Ambassador from the lower-priced Ramblers, it was neither a consumer success nor well received in the automotive press.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Moreover, overall automobile industry sales fell as the entire U.S. economy was experiencing the recession of 1960–1961.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Standard was the 250 hp (186 kW; 253 PS) 327 cu in (5.4 L) V8 with a synchromesh manual transmission.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Optional was the 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS) "power pack" version with a dual exhaust system featuring new ceramic-coated mufflers guaranteed for the life of the car.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1961 Pure Oil Company Economy Trials, designed to parallel everyday driving experiences closely, saw the Ambassador capture 9 of the first ten places in the V8 engine category and win the top of its class.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] While the unique look was meant to distinguish the Ambassador from the lower-priced Rambler models, it was neither a consumer success nor well received in the automotive press.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] By the 1962 model year, the Ambassador's platform was in its fifth season on the market.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] While Rambler sales had been good enough for third place in industry sales (behind Chevrolet and Ford), AMC's management was working on a revolutionary and somewhat costly design set to debut for the 1963 model year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] In the meantime, American Motors needed to save money.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Since the Ambassador's sales had fallen in 1961, it was decided that the car would be downsized for 1962 to directly share the body, windshield, and 108-inch (2,743 mm) wheelbase with the Classic platform.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Accordingly, the car was marketed as a **Rambler Ambassador**.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] All Ambassadors included AMC's 327 cu in (5.4 L) V8 engine, while the Rambler Classic models were limited to I6 engines.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The standard V8 was available either the regular fuel, two-barrel carburetor with 8.7:1 compression ratio, 250 hp (186 kW; 253 PS) version or the premium gasoline, four-barrel version with 9.7:1 compression ratio producing 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 108-inch (2,743 mm) wheelbase 1962 Ambassador was lighter than its 117-inch (2,972 mm) wheelbase predecessors and was a spirited performer with the 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS) 327 cu in (5.4 L) V8.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1962 Ambassador was the same vehicle and should also reach 60 mph about as quickly as did the 1957 Rambler Rebel.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1962 Ambassador received a new front end similar to the 1961 and 1962 Classic's, but with a crosshatch design, recessed center section, and **Ambassador** lettering.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] New, rectangular taillights were seen at the ends of restyled rear fenders, which lost their fins entirely.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The exterior trim was reshuffled, and a new two-door pillared sedan debuted.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] A new '400' trim line was added at the top of the trim series, with Super and Custom models remaining.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador offered even more luxurious interiors to differentiate it from the Rambler Classic.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 400 models were available with vinyl upholstered front bucket seats and headrests along with color-coordinated shag carpets.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1962 Ambassador came with a dual chamber master brake cylinder and dual-circuit brake system, thus separating the front and rear brakes so that in the event of the failure of one component, some braking function would remain.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This design was offered by only a few cars at that time.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1962 models were equipped with "Walker" (brand) flow-through mufflers and a ceramic-coated exhaust system.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Dealer-installed options included rear fender skirts and a tow hitch.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] In 1962, George Romney was elected as the new governor of Michigan, and in February, Roy Abernethy, who was responsible for the increasing sales under Romney, became CEO of AMC.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] A total of 36,171 Rambler Ambassadors were built for 1962, and AMC dropped from third to fourth place in total U.S. industry sales for the year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] In 1962, Romney resigned from AMC to run for Governor of Michigan, a position he won.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] A completely redesigned larger Rambler lineup appeared.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The new cars continued the philosophy of building smaller cars than its larger "Big Three" competitors.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, they also had a high degree of interchangeability in parts to keep tooling costs and production complexity to a minimum.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The automaker, which pioneered "styling continuity", introduced all-new styling for the 1963 model year Ambassadors and claimed that these were "functional changes .... not change just for the sake of change".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassadors featured a 4-inch (102 mm) longer wheelbase, but were 1.2-inch (30 mm) shorter due to reduced front and rear body overhangs, as well as a 3-inch (76 mm) drop in overall height.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Designed by Dick Teague, the 1963 Ambassador's shape was much tighter, cleaner, and smoother, with almost all of its parts interchangeable between it and the new Classic.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] All Ambassadors used unitized structure instead of the more rattle-prone, traditional body-on-frame construction, which was still the industry standard.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] In 1963, AMC's new 112 in (2,845 mm) wheelbase cars (Ambassadors and Classics) used a revolutionary method of unit construction, which automobile manufacturers have almost universally adopted.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] AMC Ambassador and Classics used outer panels stamped from single sheet metal panels that included door frames and outer rocker panels.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This resulted in an extremely rigid and rattle-free structure, better fit of doors into frames, production cost savings as well as reduced noise, vibration, and harshness.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The "uniside" structure was superior to the conventional production methods in which multiple smaller pieces were welded together.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] There were 30% fewer parts and the result was greater structural rigidity, quieter car operation, and an overall weight reduction of about 150 pounds (68 kilograms).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Curved side glass and push-button door handles were new and costly upgrades.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Still, they contributed to the new Rambler's handsome, elegant, and modern Mercedes-like bodyside styling by adding refinement to the car's configuration and details.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] At the time, curved side glass was used exclusively in a few much more expensive luxury cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The design attribute increased interior room and visibility, reduced wind noise, and enhanced the styling of the vehicles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador also featured a squared-off Thunderbird-type roofline.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The front end featured forward-thrusting upper and lower ends with a vertical bar "electric shaver" chrome grille insert.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador's grille was differentiated from the Classic's grille by including the Ambassador's name in script within the small horizontal bar between the upper and lower grille sections.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Round quad headlights were slightly recessed in chrome bezels mounted side by side within the grille at its outermost edges.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Overall, the new Ambassadors were described by the staff of *Automotive Fleet* magazine as "probably the finest looking cars ever produced by American Motors".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ambassadors were again available in two-door sedan, four-door sedan, and four-door station wagon body styles, but new trim lines debuted for 1963.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1963 Ambassadors were offered only with the 327 cu in (5.4 L) V8, in either 250 hp (186 kW; 253 PS) two-barrel or 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS) four-barrel versions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] AMC's smaller 287 cu in (4.7 L) V8 engine was only offered in the Classic line.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The automatic transmission was controlled by a steering column-mounted lever, replacing the previous pushbutton system.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Sales were brisk, and the redesign was billed a success, with *Motor Trend* Magazine bestowing **Car of the Year** status on the entire 1963 Rambler line, including the Ambassador.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The automaker did not have the resources of GM, Ford, and Chrysler, nor the sales volume to spread out its new model tooling and advertising costs over large production volumes; however, Richard Teague "turned these economical cars into smooth, streamlined beauties with tons of options and V-8 pep".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1964 model year introduced minor trim changes and new options for the Ambassador line as AMC emphasized the transformed Rambler American compact-sized models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The "electric-shaver" grille on the 1963 model was replaced with a flush-mounted design, and the engine and transmission options were widened.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] A two-door hardtop body style called **990-H** was added for the first time since 1957.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The base 880 models were dropped from the line.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1964 Ambassadors featured the 250 hp (186 kW; 253 PS) two-barrel 327 cu in (5.4 L) V8 as standard, with the four-barrel 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS) version as optional.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The automaker did not offer a four-speed manual transmission to compete with Ford or GM's sporty mid-size V8 offerings.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Instead, AMC offered its innovative "Twin-Stick" manual transmission.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The "Twin-stick" option consisted of a three-speed manual transmission, operated by one of the two console-mounted "sticks" in conjunction with an overdrive unit that was controlled by the second "stick" in both second and third gears.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This gave the driver the option of using five forward gears.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 990-H was the most luxurious two-door model and included the high-compression 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS) V8 as well as a specially trimmed interior featuring 2+2-style bucket seats, center armrests front and rear, as well as a console with the Twin-Stick manual or available automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Approximately 2,955 top-trim Ambassadors were built.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1964 models followed Romney's focus on practical cars under the theory that AMC could build them for longer periods of time without expensive redesigns, thus help the small automaker to achieve some economies of scale that the Big Three enjoyed.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The **Rambler Marquesa**, a concept car based on the Ambassador 990-H two-door hardtop, was designed to gauge public reaction to potential styling and feature enhancements.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] American Motors displayed it at various auto shows during the 1964 model year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Information about its existence faded following its exhibition.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] However, the show car remained in its original condition and is now on display at the Rambler Ranch in Elizabeth, Colorado, the most comprehensive collection of Nash, Rambler, and AMC vehicles and their history.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The show car is finished in a unique, two-tone paint scheme, featuring a darker, contrasting color on the roof, a popular styling trend of the mid-1960s.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The exterior also features simulated wire wheel covers with a spinner and a design to show the painted steel road wheel matching the roof finish.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Goodrich premium "Life-Saver 880" bias-ply tires featuring dual white side wall stripes and a built-in puncture sealant.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The interior features brocade fabric upholstered bucket seats with vinyl bolsters.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The luxurious textile extends to the headliner and the unique door panel trim, creating a cohesive and opulent ambiance that was the hallmark of higher-end luxury cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The center console houses the automatic transmission shifter and centrally located power window switches.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] No matter how much success the new Ramblers achieved in the marketplace, Roy Abernethy was not completely satisfied.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Using the experience he gained as an outstanding salesman as a guide, Abernethy closely looked at the direction that American Motors' competition was going and decided that the company would be much more successful if its products competed more directly with the Big Three.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Abernethy put the promise of higher profit margins per car over sales volume.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] He would achieve this by pushing all AMC vehicles further upmarket among the various market segments, shaking off the company's economy car image, and offering vehicles once again in all three major American car size classes: compact, intermediate, and full-size.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The American and Classic were strong competitors in the former two segments, so for the 1965 model year, he set his sights on turning the Ambassador into a proper full-size car by stretching the Classic's wheelbase and giving it different styling.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The general sizes of automobiles at that time were set by the industry's wheelbase length standards, rather than the modern vehicle classification by interior and cargo space.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 1965 Ambassador represented a fundamental shift in corporate ideology, a shift away from primarily fuel-efficient vehicles, to bigger, faster, and potentially more profitable cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Although the Ambassador rode the same platform as its 1963 and 1964 forebears, the 1965 models looked all-new.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] American Motors' designer Dick Teague styled the 1965 Ambassador with panache and gave the car an overall integrated look.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] *Motor Trend* magazine agreed, calling it a "strikingly handsome automobile".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The overall linear design look could be described as "chunky" or "chiseled".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] All Ambassadors were built on a 116-inch (2,946 mm) wheelbase, or four inches (100 mm) longer than the Classic models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Teague extended the beltline level from the stacked quad headlights to the vertical taillamps to stretch the cars visually.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador featured longer, squared-off rear fenders with vertical wrap-around taillights, taller trunk lid, squared-off rear bumper-mounted low, and squarer rear wheel arches.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] At the front, the Ambassador again sparked minor controversy with its new vertically stacked quad headlights, slightly recessed in their bezels, as they flanked an all-new horizontal bar grille.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This new wall-to-wall grille projected horizontally in the center to create an effect somewhat opposite to the 1963's grille treatment.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The front-end design provided a bold, rugged appearance.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] According to automotive journalists. the new Ambassadors were as attractive as anything built by AMC's Detroit-based competitors, and with a list price of around $3,000, few could quibble about the cost of ownership.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] As was the case before 1962, the Ambassador's entire extra wheelbase was ahead of the cowl, meaning that interior volume was the same as the intermediate-sized Classic.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Another new body style debuted in the Ambassador lineup for 1965: an attractive new convertible offered as part of the 990 series.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] This was the first time a convertible was offered in the Ambassador line since 1948.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ambassador body styles (except station wagons with three rows of seats and the 990-H hardtop) offered seating for six passengers, with hardtops and convertibles having the option of bucket seats with a center console and floor shifter.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The Ambassador 990-H was a premium two-door hardtop model, available only in five-passenger form with the standard front bucket seats featuring fold-down center armrests and a retracting rear seat center armrest.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ambassadors also saw an expanded list of trim lines, convenience options, and engine choices.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Interiors were redesigned and featured a new dashboard.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 990 and 990-H models were continued, while the 880 models were the new economy leaders in the 1965 Ambassador line.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Still, even the $2,512 price for the two-door sedan was not attractive compared to the models with better trim, bucket seats, and unique interiors.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Ambassadors came standard with AMC's new 232 cu in (3.8 L) Inline-6 engine, which was the first time since 1956 that an Ambassador was available with six cylinders.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Far more popular in the Ambassador, however, were the two time-tested 287 and 327 cu in (4.7 and 5.4 L) AMC V8 engines.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] American Motors' management decided that the Ambassador could once again be available with a standard six-cylinder engine because its full-size competitors (e. g.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Bel Air and Impala, Ford Custom 500 and Galaxie, as well as Plymouth Fury) came with six-cylinder engines as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] They, therefore, appealed to a broader range of customers than the Ambassador was getting.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Also, since the Classic was now smaller and styled differently, the Ambassador six-cylinder would not cannibalize Classic six sales, which were the company's sales volume leaders.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The changes were on target as sales of the repositioned Ambassador more than tripled.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The standard six-cylinder engine now featured larger valves making them the same as on the V8s.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The front seatbacks were redesigned to offer additional legroom for rear-seat passengers with the popular reclining front seat backs now having seven positions, compared to the previous five.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Front Bendix disc brakes with power assist were now optional.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Tom Magliozzi, one of the brothers hosting the *Car Talk* radio talk show, owned a black 1965 AMC Ambassador convertible that he called my "sleek black beauty" and wanted another one when asked "if you could have any car, new or old, what it would be?
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] American Motors campaigned the **Rambler Attaché**, a specially prepared Ambassador convertible, for the auto show circuit.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] It was finished in deep-indigo pearlescent paint with red body side pinstripes, and the car was upgraded to real chrome wire wheels.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The hood ornament featured a "crown-like Ambassador crest" while the interior's bucket seats were upholstered in indigo leather with ruby-red inserts.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Only minor changes were introduced for the 1966 Ambassador range.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The V-shaped horizontal louver spanned unbroken between the headlamps, and the effect was continued with twin rectangular trim pieces attached to the side of the front fenders at their leading edges by the headlamps.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The styling effect was repeated in the new vertical wraparound taillamps, with the top-line models receiving a twin set of horizontal ribbed moldings across the back of the trunk lid that simulated the look of the front grille.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The two-door hardtop received a redesigned roofline that was angular in appearance with angle-cut rear side windows and a rectangular rear window.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The backlight no longer curved and wrapped slightly around the C-pillars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The changes made for a more "formal" notchback look that was popular at the time.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Station wagons also received a new roof (that did not have as pronounced dip over the rear cargo area) as well as a redesigned tailgate and optional simulated woodgrain exterior side panels.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Available with two rows of seats with a standard bottom-hinged tailgate with electric, fully retracting rear window or an optional rear-facing third-row that featured a left side-hinged rear door, with a regular exterior door handle on the right side.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] All station wagons carried a **Cross Country** badge.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The two-door sedan was the price leader at $2,404 but finished with the fewest sales for the model year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The more popular and higher trimmed 990 models were available in sedan, wagon, hardtop, and convertible versions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Options included a vinyl roof, wire wheel covers, AM/FM radio, adjustable steering wheel, and cruise control.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] A new luxury **DPL** sub-model (short for "Diplomat") two-door hardtop debuted at the top of the range.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The DPL included unique lower body side trim and numerous standard convenience items such as reclining bucket seats upholstered in brocade fabrics or optional vinyl.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] An optional interior trim featured houndstooth fabric and included two throw pillows.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The DPL model was aimed to compete with the new, more upscale trimmed Plymouth VIP, Ford LTD, Chevrolet Caprice and Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6, as well as the 287 and 327 cu in (4.7 and 5.4 L) V8s remained in the line, but transmission selections now included a new console-mounted four-speed manual.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Most Ambassadors continued to be ordered with automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Perhaps the biggest change, however, was that the Ambassador lost its historic Rambler nameplate, as the car was now marketed as the "American Motors Ambassador" or "AMC Ambassador".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Abernethy was again responsible for this marketing move, as he attempted to move the stylish new Ambassador even further upmarket.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] To him, that meant that the Rambler name and its economy car image would be eschewed to give the car a clean slate in a market that was turning away from a focus on economy and toward V8 performance.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] The evidence suggests that Abernethy was on the right track with moving the Ambassador upscale to compete with other manufacturers' luxury models as sales of the AMC's flagship jumped from 18,647 in 1964 to over 64,000 in 1965, and then in 1966, they went to more than 71,000.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p01] Although the Ambassador accounted for a mere fraction of total passenger car sales in the U.S., it was a step in bringing AMC's products in line with what the consumer of the day wanted.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors introduced a completely restyled, longer, lower, and wider Ambassador for the 1967 model year, now riding on a 118 in (2,997 mm) wheelbase, or two inches (51 mm) longer than before.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador's platform was four inches (100 mm) longer than the new Rambler Rebel's 114-inch (2,896 mm) wheelbase.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador was positioned in the standard-size category, against traditional big cars such as Ford Galaxie, Chevrolet Impala, and Plymouth Fury.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The convertible was offered again—this time in DPL trim—for 1967; but this would be the final year with 1,260 built.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] It featured an all-new "split stack" folding mechanism with concealed side rails that did not intrude into the backseat area, thus offering room for three adult passengers in the rear.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The car once again looked completely new, with a more rounded appearance that sported sweeping rooflines, "coke-bottle" fenders, greater glass area, and a recessed grille that bowed forward less than that of the 1965–66 models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Taillights were wider, rectangular, and divided by one central vertical bar.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] *Motor Trend* magazine described the all-new styling of the new Ambassador as "attractive" and "more graceful and easier on the eye in '67".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 880 two-door sedans featured the identical roofline as the hardtops, but had slim B-pillars that gave them a more open-air "coupe" appearance and were marketed as "Sports Sedans".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 880 trim was also available in four-door sedan and station wagon versions, but more popular were the better equipped and more upscale 990 models came in four-door sedan, station wagon, and two-door hardtop body styles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Adding more elegance to DPL two-door hardtops and convertibles was the optional "Satin-Chrome" finish (paint code P-42) for the lower body side replacing the standard full-length stainless steel rocker moldings.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A black or white vinyl cover was optional on 990 and DPL sedans and hardtops.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 990 **Cross Country** station wagons were available with 3M's "Di-noc" simulated wood-grain body side panels trimmed in a slim stainless steel frame.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The full-sized Ambassador featured a lengthy list of standard features and options.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The interiors "rival more expensive cars for luxury and quality, yet are durable enough to take years of normal wear".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The premium materials and fittings included wood-grain trim and even an optional "Custom" package with unique upholstery and two matching pillows.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Ambassador DPL hardtops included reclining bucket seats with a center armrest between them (with a center cushion for a third occupant or a floor console with gear selector), as well as a foldaway center armrest for the rear seat.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The new safety-oriented instrument panel grouped all gauges and controls in front of the driver, with the rest of the dashboard pushed forward and away from the passengers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Focusing on safety, there were now no protruding knobs, the steering column was designed to collapse under impact, and the steering wheel was smaller than previous Ambassadors.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The long-lived "GEN-1" family of AMC V8 engines was replaced by an all-new line of 290 and 343 cu in (4.8 and 5.6 L) engines that debuted for 1966 in the Rambler American.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] These V8s were an all-new design featuring a thin-wall-casting block, heads, and manifold.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] With a four-barrel carburetor and dual exhaust, the 343 cu in (5.6 L) produced 280 bhp (209 kW) at 4800 rpm and 365 lb⋅ft (495 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A new four-link trailing-arm rear suspension system eliminated the old torque tube design, providing a more comfortable coil spring ride.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors promoted the new 1967 Ambassador as an "uncompromising automobile with the red carpet ride" in print advertisements, as well as in an innovative TV commercial.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] However, sales of the redesigned models were disappointing due to customer confusion caused by the entire company's abrupt upmarket push, which seemed uncomfortably "me too" to the traditional domestic Big Three's customers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] They also alienated American Motors' loyal buyer base.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Abernethy's ideas for entering new markets were not working.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] These strategy changes led to a new round of financial problems for American Motors.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Because of this, Abernathy was later that year released from AMC by its board of directors and replaced by William V.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors provided specialized fleet options for commercial and municipal customers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Taxi and police versions were subjected to heavy use and the options were not available to the general public.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A purchase order was made by the General Services Administration (GSA) of 3,745 Ambassador base 880 four-door sedans for use by the United States Postal Service (USPS), most to be built in factory right-hand-drive.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] There were six vehicles for review for this purchase and tested was a left-hand drive AMC Ambassador 880 sedan with its back seat removed.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Not all of the units ordered for the postal service had right-hand drive.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Specifications included factory heavy-duty fleet options such as rubber floor mats, upholstery, and the deletion of the rear seat.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Most came with the base 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6 engine along with column-shift automatic transmission and "Twin-Grip" (limited-slip differential).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] All came with an identification metal plate on the dash near the ashtray.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors took advantage of this large fleet order to market the 1967 Ambassadors.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Print advertisements in popular magazines headlined "We Deliver" with a picture of the USPS vehicles, while other ads described that Ambassadors would provide safety, reliability, and a "red-carpet" ride.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The engineering to make the cars right-hand-drive served as the template for other American Motors vehicles based on the Ambassador platform, destined for foreign right-hand-drive markets such as Australia, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Matador was built in Australia until 1976 in this way.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The fastback Marlin two-door hardtop that was previously built on the Rambler Classic platform in 1965 and 1966, was continued for 1967, but was now based on the larger Ambassador platform.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The total redesign of the related AMC intermediate and full-size platforms made it easy for the personal-luxury model shift to the Ambassador's longer 118 in (2,997 mm) wheelbase.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] It now featured the Ambassador's front end, longer hood, and luxury appointments with an even longer fastback roofline than the previous versions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The opinion of professional auto stylists is that the Ambassador-based design "produced the best result.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors was a pioneer in air conditioning through its Kelvinator refrigerator division.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] AMC's marketing chief Bill McNealy wanted to make the Ambassador stand out in a crowded market segment and decided to add more significant distinction to the 1968 Ambassador line by making the All Weather A/C system as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This was the first time any volume car manufacturer had done so, something that even Cadillac and Lincoln had not offered on their luxury cars – although some of them were priced at more than twice as much as Ambassador.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Most Ambassadors were ordered with air conditioning, so AMC garnered effective marketing distinction at little cost by including it with the 1968 model year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] While all Ambassadors came with it as standard, consumers could order the car without air as a "delete option" and decrease the price by $218.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] As AMC pointed out in their advertising campaign for the Ambassador, the only other major automaker that offered air conditioning as standard equipment on its cars in 1968 was Rolls-Royce.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Air conditioning was standard only on Cadillac limousines.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Because of slow sales during the 1967 model year, both the top trim convertible and the basic two-door models were dropped for 1968.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The new Ambassador lineup consisted of a base two-door hardtop and a four-door sedan, a mid-level DPL in three body styles (two-door hardtop, four-door sedan, and station wagon), and a new top-of-the-line SST available as a two-door hardtop or a four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The personal luxury fastback Marlin that was based on the Ambassador platform was also discontinued to make way for the smaller 1968 AMC Javelin in the pony car segment.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The high-level of standard equipment had marketing brochures asking, “Could that SST stand for Sensational Straight Through?" while reviews described the 1968 Ambassador SST as "The Kenosha Cadillac".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Taillights were now recessed in body-color bezels divided by a single central horizontal bar.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Front headlight bezels were now made of nylon and similarly body-colored.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A new injection-molded ABS thermoplastic polymer grille was dominated by a horizontal bar that extended forward in the center from the sides, while its outline had squared off edges that wrapped ahead into the inner headlight extensions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Fender-mounted marker lights were added at the front and rear as standard equipment, as the U.S.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) regulations mandated their application (along with seat belts beginning January 1, 1968) to all passenger cars sold in the United States for 1968.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] However, AMC's most enduring styling feature debuted on the Ambassador for 1968, as flush-mounted paddle-style door handles replaced the former push-button units on all American Motors cars, save the compact Rambler American.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The heavy, chromed door handles with push-buttons on the 1967 models were the most protruding body side feature, making the cars 78.4 in (1,991 mm) wide.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1968 versions have the same bodyside and door sheetmetal, but the AMC's new door handle design was set completely flat against the door skin, eliminating the snag hazard and reducing the car's width to 77.2 in (1,961 mm).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The practical and "disarmingly simple design" predated safety-related mandates and industry norms.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The interior locking was no longer by the traditional windowsill push-button, but a lever set into the armrest.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Front-wheel alignment was made more accessible and more accurate by moving the camber adjustment from the upper to the lower control arm on the double wishbone suspension, and the caster angle adjustments also moved from the upper control arm to the drag strut.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] At midyear, AMC's new top engine, the AMX 390 cu in (6.4 L) 315 hp (235 kW; 319 PS) V8, became an option in the Ambassador line, bringing the total engine options up to four.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] In June 1967, American Motors started a new advertising campaign created by Mary Wells Lawrence of the Wells, Rich, and Greene marketing agency.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The US$12 million AMC account was high-profile assignment and helped established the agency as innovative and daring in its approach.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The new advertising violated the convention of not directly attacking the competition, and AMC's campaigns became highly controversial.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The publicity worked with AMC's total retail sales improving 13% for the fiscal year, but 1968 Ambassador numbers were slightly down.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This strategy allowed AMC to offer a perceived premium experience in a more manageable package, appealing to a segment of consumers seeking refinement without the bulk of traditional American luxury cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] In 1969, the Ambassador received a major restyling, with a 4-inch (102 mm) gain in overall length and wheelbase.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 122-inch (3,099 mm) wheelbase was accompanied by an increase in front and rear track from 58.5 to 60 inches (1,486 to 1,524 mm).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The front end appearance was revised with new quad headlight clusters mounted horizontally in a new molded plastic grille.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The grille was blacked out, with a chrome horizontal bar connecting the headlight clusters.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The hood was redesigned to accommodate the grille's raised center portion, and it faintly recalled Packard's classic grille/hood combination.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Dick Teague, AMC's Vice President of Styling, had worked at the luxury car manufacturer before joining AMC.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Parking lights were rectangular and mounted horizontally in recessed wells in the front bumper, just beneath each set of headlights.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The entire front fascia leaned forward slightly to lend an air of forward motion to the car's appearance.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] At the rear, ribbed rectangular taillights were mounted inboard the Ambassador's rearward-thrusting rear fenders.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Square ribbed marker lights of similar height were mounted at the trailing edge of each fender side.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The deck lid had a slightly higher lift-over for cargo access.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The base and DPL models had no bright trim panel between the taillights, while the top-line SST versions featured a panel with a red finish to match the taillights.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Station wagons saw vertical wraparound taillights replacing the previous "hooded" units, which were not visible from the side.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1969 AMC Ambassador was a smooth, powerful, well-proportioned sedan that did not look like anything else on the road.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The interiors were upgraded, and a new deeply hooded dashboard clustered instruments and controls in front of the driver.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] There was an increased emphasis on luxury-type trim and features by buyers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The base model two-door hardtop Ambassador was no longer offered for the 1969 model year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] One aspect of this new advertising theme included many AMC dealers inviting prospective customers to call and request a "demonstration ride", in which a uniformed chauffeur would arrive at the prospect's home and drive them around in an Ambassador SST sedan.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] AMC's efforts worked, and Ambassador sales increased again.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Not only did AMC promote the 1969 Ambassador as having a "limousine" ride and deluxe appointments, but Chicago auto leasing executive, Robert Estes, had the Armbruster/Stageway Company convert Ambassadors into real 24-foot (7.3 m) limousines riding on a 158-inch (4,013 mm) wheelbase.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Known as the **Royale Stretch Limo**, one was owned by the State of Wisconsin as the official vehicle for Governor Warren Knowles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The conversions were unusual because they did not keep the stock rear doors—as is typical in most limos.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The back doors were welded shut, and the Ambassadors were lengthened by inserting a section just behind the original B-pillar that had an entirely new central door in this center, making a large opening for entry and egress.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Four-inch (100 mm) steel "I-beams" bridge the expanse created by the stretch.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Power comes from the "AMX" 315 hp (235 kW; 319 PS) 390 cu in (6.4 L) V8 engine backed with the BorgWarner automatic transmission and a "Twin-Grip" limited-slip differential with 3.15 gears.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The most significant change by AMC for the 1970 model year was the launch of the new compact Hornet that not only replaced the Rambler American, but also became the platform for several types of vehicles through its discontinuation in 1988.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] However, all car lines received changes and updates for 1970.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1970 AMC Ambassadors were announced on 1 October 1969, featuring new rear end styling for the two-door hardtops and four-door sedans while the station wagons gained a new roof panel to accommodate a longer 6-foot (1,829 mm) luggage rack, which was standard.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The luxury-positioned Ambassador continued to offer air conditioning as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Model designations continued with the "SST" and the "DPL" while the fleet-oriented "Basic" version was offered only as a four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The "basic" model was not available for export markets.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The two-door hardtops and four-door sedans featured a new design that was shared by the intermediate 1970 AMC Rebel.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Restyling on the two-door versions consisted of a sloping roofline into the rear deck and broad C-pillars highlighted by upswept reverse-angle quarter windows.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The beltline kicked up at the point where the hardtop's rear windows swept upward and tapered back to the fender end, meeting a new loop-type rear bumper with integrated rear lamps.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] On the four-door sedans, the roofline featured slimmer C-pillars and squared-off rear door windows, meeting a beltline that kicked up beneath the trailing edge of each rear door window.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The beltline tapered back to the same rear fascia as on the two-door hardtops.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The rear bumper on the hardtops and sedans contained a new ribbed taillight lens that stretched wall-to-wall and included twin square white reverse light lenses in its center.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The station wagon's rear end was mostly unchanged from the 1969 versions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] It included the dual-swing tailgate that could open down to extend even with the load bed or open like a door on its hinges on the left side, facilitating egress for the optional rear-facing third-row seat for two passengers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A power lift tailgate window was included with the three-row station wagons.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] All Ambassadors received a new extruded aluminum grille at the front, featuring several widely spaced slim bright horizontal bars with one larger, body-colored filled horizontal bar extending to each headlight cluster.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador was available in fourteen exterior colors, 31 two-tone combinations (including the bodyside and tailgate on DPL station wagons, while SST included wood-grained vinyl exterior trim), and a vinyl roof cover in black, white, or blue was optional for DPL and SST hardtops and sedans.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Interior choices included seats with coil springs and upscale brocade upholstery or available channeled velour in SST sedans.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Standard on the Basic and DPL models was a non-reclining full-width front bench seat for three passengers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The SST included 50-50 individual reclining front seats.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The two-door hardtop SST was available with high-back bucket seats in fabric or vinyl.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] They came with an armrest and a center cushion with the standard column-shifted automatic or optional center console-mounted shifter.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 290 cu in (4.8 L) V8 was replaced for 1970 by a new 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This 210 hp (157 kW; 213 PS) at 4400 rpm and 305 pound force-feet (414 N⋅m) of torque at 2800 rpm was the standard engine on all DPL and SST models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 343 cu in (5.6 L) V8 was also supplanted by a 360 cu in (5.9 L) engine in either two-barrel, regular gasoline, or high-output, four-barrel, premium fuel versions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The four-barrel "AMX" 390 cu in (6.4 L) V8 engine was optional, producing 325 hp (242 kW; 330 PS) at 3200 rpm and 420 pound force-feet (569 N⋅m) of torque at 3200 rpm.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Only the base model positioned as a fleet vehicle had a 232 cu in (3.8 L) I6 engine as standard.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The three-speed automatic transmission was standard on Ambassador DPL and SST models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] New for the 1970 model year were two stripe whitewalls.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The images of the Ambassador in AMC's 1970 marketing materials featured the new design replacing the previous single whitewall option.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] However, the dual white stripe tire popularity did not last long.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Factory audio options included vertically instrument panel-mounted AM or AM/FM radios, as well as an additional eight-track stereo tape player for sedans and hardtops.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Marketing for the 1970 AMC Ambassador focused on it being a rich-looking car that was highly affordable.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The promotion noted the Ambassador is AMC's finest car, like the Cadillac at General Motors, Lincoln Continental is Ford's, and Imperial is Chrysler's, but "about the size of their Impalas, Galaxies, and Furys" that were considered ordinary models at the time.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador, built on a 122 in (3,099 mm) wheelbase was compared to the final generation of Lincoln's Town Car 123.7 in (3,142 mm) wheelbase as sharing dimensions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors marketing agency used innovative techniques such as comparative and "off-beat" ads as well as the heavy use of TV spots to emphasize exciting cars and a youthful image.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Not yet well known at the time, Robert De Niro was featured in television advertisements as an accountant who just finished college and purchased a luxurious car.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Little Italy, Manhattan, is featured as the backdrop and there are caricatures of Italian Americans.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The advertisement resembles the setting of *The Godfather*, but was made two years before that film and four years before De Niro joined that film series.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] An estimated 58,900 AMC Ambassadors were produced for the 1970 model year with an average MSRP of $3,677.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1971 AMC Ambassador line of cars received minor changes following its major redesign in 1970.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The marketing for the year adopted a "David vs.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The agency "started running sassy, combative ads" to differentiate AMC's cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] One answer to this challenge was by AMC including an extensive list of standard features, advantages, and benefits to stand out against its larger competitors.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] For the 1971 model year, AMC streamlined the Ambassador lineup.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The previously unnamed base model was dropped, with the sedan-only DPL trim line taking its place as the entry-level offering.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A new top-of-the-line **Brougham** trim was introduced, positioned above the mid-range SST models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The SST and Brougham were available in two-door hardtop, four-door sedan, and station wagon body styles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Part of AMC's value proposition was including premium features as standard.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] All Ambassadors came equipped with a BorgWarner "Shift-Command" automatic transmission, removing the manual transmission option from the lineup.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The DPL model featured AMC's new 258 cu in (4.2 L) I6 engine, rated at 150 hp (112 kW; 152 PS) with a seven-main bearing design for improved durability.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The SST and Brougham models included the 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine, rated at 210 hp (157 kW), as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Optional engines included 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 in a 8.5:1 compression model with a two-barrel carburetor using regular gasoline or a high-compression, four-barrel version that required premium fuel.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The top engine option was a powerful new 401 cu in (6.6 L), 335 hp (250 kW) V8 that replaced the previous "AMX" 390 cu in (6.4 L) version.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1971 Ambassador's styling changes were concentrated on the front and rear of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The front end featured a new distinctively styled grille with a bright surround with rounded edges.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The headlights were housed in chrome pods that flanked the recessed "natural" cast pot metal grille insert with a bright vertical bar pattern.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A second set of parking lights was integrated into the fender extension, a design change that eliminated the need for separate front marker lights and gave the car a cleaner look.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The taillights on the two-door hardtops and four-door sedans remained a full-width, "wall-to-wall" design.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] However, the twin backup lights were repositioned from the center of the taillight cluster to a more outboard location.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The station wagon received a new design for its optional woodgrain side trim, which flowed in a downward arc from the front fender, a styling cue reminiscent of the "sweep spear" on the Buick Skylark.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The dual-hinged station wagon tailgate was standard and for added safety, the woodgrain trim on it was made reflective.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador's durability made it a popular choice for fleet buyers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The base DPL sedan was offered various heavy-duty packages for police departments, taxicab companies, and government agencies.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] They were equipped with the more powerful 360 cu in (5.9 L) or 401 cu in (6.6 L) V8 engines for police cruisers and support vehicles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Minor changes were incorporated in 1972 Ambassadors, as AMC's most significant news for the year was the addition of the innovative **AMC Buyer Protection Plan**, which included the industry's first 12-month or 12,000-mile (19,000 km) bumper-to-bumper warranty.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This was the first time an automaker promised to repair anything wrong with the car (except for tires) and owners were provided with a toll-free telephone number to the company, as well as a complimentary loaner car if a warranty repair took overnight.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This backing also included mechanical upgrades to increase durability and quality, such as the standardization of electric windshield wipers on all model lines, replacing AMC's vacuum-powered units, and better interior trims.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The base Ambassador DPL model was canceled, with three body styles now available in SST and Brougham trim.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Fleet purchasers could order plain Ambassadors in Police Pursuit Vehicle (PPV) or Special Service Package (SSP) versions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A six-cylinder engine was no longer available; thus, the Ambassador became an exclusively V8-engined car for the first time since 1964.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This made the Ambassador the only volume-produced American car that included air conditioning, power brakes, automatic transmission, and a V8 engine as standard equipment; all while being priced less than the Big Three's full-sized cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The base engine was the 304 cu in (5.0 L) with two 360 cu in (5.9 L) or a 401 cu in (6.6 L) versions optional.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The engines were designed to operate on regular-grade, low-lead, or unleaded types of gasoline.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] All were based on the engine designs responsible for AMC winning the 1971–1972 Trans-Am Series.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The BorgWarner transmission was replaced by the "Torque-Command" (TorqueFlite) three-speed automatic sourced from Chrysler.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Styling changes on the 1972 Ambassador were minimal and consisted of a new crosshatch cast metal grille with bright trim and new integrated fender extension mounted side marker lamps on the front.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Brougham station wagons now included a roof rack, rear air deflector, as well as 3M "Di-noc" woodgrain trim on body sides and tailgate.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A *Popular Mechanics* magazine survey after driving a total of 1,000,000 miles (1,609,344 km) found Ambassador owners were pleased with their cars, describing them to be "very comfortable to drive and ride in" with handling listed as a top "specific like" by half of the drivers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A very high percentage (92%) would buy one again.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Although the Buyer Protection Plan was listed by only 8.5% as a reason to buy an Ambassador, owners valued the smaller AMC dealers that "had more time to be courteous and to pay personal attention to customers".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] By focusing on quality, the smallest domestic automaker was profitable in 1972, earning US$30.2 million (the highest net profit achieved by AMC since 1964) on $4 billion in sales.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The SST models were dropped from the line, as all 1973 Ambassadors now came in one high-level "Brougham" trim.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Ten popular items, including an AM radio, power disc brakes, tinted glass, and whitewall tires were added to the already extensive standard equipment list that included air conditioning, V8 engine, and automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador line "maintains its reputation as one of the industry's most completely equipped cars".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Multiple improvements in quality were designed to reinforce the new "Extended Buyer Protection Plan" exclusive to AMC cars that provided complete maintenance coverage for two years or 24,000 miles (38,624 km).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] In range rationalization to a single trim available in two-door hardtop, four-door sedan, and station wagon body versions, the styling changes for the 1973 Ambassadors were minimal.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Heftier front and rear bumpers were included to comply with new U.S.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) regulations that required all passenger cars to withstand a 5-mile-per-hour (8 km/h) front and a 2.5-mile-per-hour (4 km/h) rear impacts without damage to the engine, lights, and safety equipment.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Ambassadors complied with the regulation by incorporating a stronger front bumper equipped with self-restoring telescoping shock absorbers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Designed to "give" as much as 3.5 in (89 mm), it jutted slightly forward from the front fascia and incorporated flexible trim matching the body paint.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This bumper also featured a more prominent horizontal rubber guard at its upper portion near the grille, thus eliminating the need for a pair of vertical chrome bumper guards that were optional before.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The grille gained heavier horizontal bars, and headlight bezels took on blackout trim in their recessed portions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The rear bumper gained vertical black rubber bumper guards, replacing a pair of similar and previously optional chrome bumper guards.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The taillight panel on sedans and hardtops also got a blackout surround and now held four rectangular lenses each trimmed with a three-by-four grid overlay, the outer and inner lenses separated by the backup lamps and the two inner ones separated by the Ambassador eagle-and-shield emblem.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Finally, the woodgrain paneling on station wagons was moved below the side moldings.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Model year production for AMC increased 25%, outperforming the industry average production increase by 75%, with only a slightly changed product in the showrooms.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1974 model year AMC Ambassadors represented the eighth and final generation of AMC's flagship line, differing markedly in styling and interior finish from their 1970 through 1973 predecessors.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This redesign occurred just as the 1973 oil crisis dramatically impacted the American automotive landscape, sparking nationwide gasoline rationing due to the oil embargo and a rapid shift in consumer preferences towards smaller, more fuel-efficient vehicles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1974 Ambassador underwent a comprehensive restyling, becoming the longest AMC-built version at 217.8 in (5,532 mm).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] While retaining its previous 122 in (3,099 mm) wheelbase, the new styling was specifically engineered to accommodate the new federal energy-absorbing bumpers at both the front and rear.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador's overall length increased by 8.2-inch (208 mm) compared to its 1972 counterpart, the last year without bumper standards.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This growth is partly attributed to its larger rear bumper and an unusually long front nose.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Most full-sized competitor models saw significant increases, except for Chevrolet, which grew 2.8 in (71 mm) during the same period, as its previous bumpers were already pushed out from the bodywork.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The front end of the 1974 Ambassador sedan and wagon received an all-new hood, grille, and bumper.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The grille featured a new squared-off loop-type design surrounding the circular, recessed quad headlights, with a distinctive forward-protruding center.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The grille insert displayed a crosshatch pattern dominated by two thick horizontal bars that connected the headlight bezels.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] New amber parking lights were integrated between these bars, following the grille's protrusion forward and overlaid by its crosshatch trim.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The headlamp bezels were again blacked out in their recessed areas.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The new hood and front bumper followed the grille's central protrusion, giving the car a subtle "coffin nose" look.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The contemporary Matador sedan received a similar frontal treatment in 1974, though with a much more pronounced effect and different single headlamp clusters, hood, and grille inserts.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] At the rear, the new bumper was substantially larger and backed by shock absorbers, designed to comply with new National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) regulations requiring standardized front and rear bumpers to withstand a 5-mile-per-hour (8 km/h) impact without damage.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] On sedans, the rear fenders received fiberglass caps that wrapped inward, creating a recessed space for the carryover decklid.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Within this space, new rectangular taillight housings were mounted, featuring taller white backup lights positioned inboard of the taillights.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The license plate was relocated from the rear bumper to the area between these new taillight assemblies, with the entire taillight and license plate system on sedans encircled by a chrome trim loop.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Both the Ambassador and Matador sedans shared this new rear-end styling.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The station wagons' cargo area and rear design remained similar to previous Ambassadors, save for the massive new bumper and revised taillamps.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] For 1974, the Ambassador Brougham lineup was simplified, no longer offering a two-door hardtop.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This left only the four-door sedan and station wagon body styles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The cancellation of the hardtop was partly due to low sales of the previous Ambassador two-door models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Also, it coincided with the introduction of the all-new 1974 Matador coupe.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The two-door featured a wide B-pillar, a distinctive long hood, and a short rear deck.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Its design was lauded by *Car and Driver* as the "Best Styled Car of 1974" on the magazine cover, and the road test noted how it avoided typical mid-1970s styling hallmarks like imitation landau bars and opera lights.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The interiors featured luxurious upholstery and trim, including standard 50-50, individually adjustable, reclining front seats.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The dashboard received an all-new instrument panel incorporating soft-plastic control knobs with international symbols.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Standard "Abbington" fabric upholstery was featured on sedan bench seats, while ventilated woven vinyl trim was standard for wagon bench seats.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Optional "Pavillion" fabric was available on individual reclining seats for sedan and station wagon, in black, green, blue, and cinnamon.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador station wagon offered standard two-row bench seats for six passengers, with an optional rear-facing third row to accommodate eight seat-belted passengers.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] As standard equipment, wagons came with numerous practical, appearance, and comfort features, including a versatile two-way-opening tailgate (hinged at the bottom for loading or hauling long cargo, and hinged at the side to open like a door for easy entry/exit).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Exterior trim included wood-grained semi-transparent vinyl side and rear panels, a full-length roof rack, and a chrome and wood-grain roof air deflector designed to help keep the tailgate window clean.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Ordering the station wagon without the 3M "Di-noc" exterior body trim was possible.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Powertrain selections for 1974 remained consistent with 1973, with only V8 engines and automatic transmissions available.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The standard engine was the 304 cu in (5.0 L), with the 360 cu in (5.9 L) and 401 cu in (6.6 L) V8s available.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Other mechanical enhancements for 1974 included a larger-capacity fuel tank, increased to 24.9 US gal (94 L; 21 imp gal) for sedans (wagons continued with 17.5 US gal (66 L; 15 imp gal)), and a 62-ampere alternator.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] New sound insulation was added, making the Ambassador even quieter.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] All 1974 Ambassadors came with a lengthy list of standard equipment typically optional on competing makes, underscoring its flagship status.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] These included comfort items such as air conditioning, an AM radio, and a vanity mirror, as well as appearance enhancements like pin striping and whitewall tires.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Standard safety features included power steering and power front disc brakes.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1974 model year proved challenging for all full-size vehicles in the American market, regardless of the automaker, as the 1973 oil crisis triggered a significant shift in consumer focus towards smaller, more fuel-efficient cars.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The overall full-sized, low-priced market segment experienced a sharp 37% drop in sales.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] At the same time, AMC was facing increasing demand for its smaller-sized Gremlin and Hornet models, and the automaker was struggling to keep up with production of these more economical cars by 1974.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The company was also preparing for the highly anticipated introduction of the Pacer.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors decided to discontinue the Ambassador (as well as the Javelin in the shrinking pony car segment) after the 1974 model year to simplify production lines by reducing the number of different models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] In June 1974, the final AMC Ambassador rolled off the Kenosha, Wisconsin assembly line.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This marked the end of a nameplate that had been in continuous production in some form for 48 years.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Total production for the 1974 Ambassador consisted of 17,901 sedans and 7,070 station wagons, for a combined total of 24,971 Ambassadors during its final model year.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Assembly of IKA Ramblers began in 1962, with the Argentinean cars being the 1961 U.S. versions, but equipped with 226 cu in (3.70 L) Continental I6 engines producing 119 hp (89 kW; 121 PS) at 4000 rpm, along with a steering column-mounted manual three-speed transmission.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador 440 was the top-trim IKA model available only as a four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The completely new generation models by AMC in the U.S. for the 1963 model year were also replicated by IKA.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador sedan came exclusively in 990 trim, and it revolutionized the Argentine automotive market by introducing innovations that included power steering, power windows, and factory-installed air conditioning.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Ambassador line was redesigned for 1965 in the U.S., as well as for Argentina.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] All IKA Rambler models now featured the 230.5 cu in (3.78 L) overhead camshaft (OHC) straight-six "Tornado Interceptor" engines producing 145 hp (108 kW; 147 PS) at 4200 rpm.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] They were originally developed by Kaiser Motors in the U.S. for the 1963 Jeep Gladiator pickups and Wagoneer vehicles.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The engine was now produced in Argentina, and it increased the domestic (locally sourced) content of IKA automobiles to lower taxes (tariffs).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The new IKA Ambassador 990 sedans were further upgraded to steering column-mounted ZF four-speed manual transmissions, front disc brakes, front reclining bucket seats with center cushion and armrest, as well as luxury features that included power windows and air conditioning.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A road test by *Revista Parabrisas* magazine described the 1965 IKA Rambler Ambassador 990 as "soft, opulent, and smooth ride at all speeds... something big, luxurious and complete... the highest expression of comfort tested so far by the magazine".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Stretch versions of the IKA Rambler Ambassador were used as official government limousines.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The "Presidential" models featured a longer rear door and side window, as well as broader C-pillar with padded vinyl roof cover and a small rear window.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Although not documented by AMI records, it is concluded that 20 right-hand drive 1970 Ambassadors were fully imported from Kenosha, apparently 16 two-door hardtops and 4 four-door sedans.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] A possible reason was that it may have been a holding action while AMI was preparing for the assembly of the new 1970 Rebel.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] All were fitted with AMC's new 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 and automatic transmission with floor shift.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The dash and instrument pack of the 1967 Ambassador, which had been converted and used in the RHD Ambassadors assembled for the U.S.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Postal Service, was standard in all assembly kits for the Rebel and Matador included in all factory-right-hand drive Rebels, Matadors, and Ambassadors exported to the United Kingdom.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Rambler vehicles were marketed in Costa Rica since 1959 through **Purdy Motor**.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] New local content regulations enacted during the 1960s effectively required vehicles sold in those markets to be assembled from knock-down kits.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] An assembly plant for Rambler and Toyota vehicles was established, **ECASA**, and the first Ramblers were produced in Costa Rica by the end of 1965.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The company built Ambassadors and other AMC models through 1970, with Toyota increasing ownership of ECASA.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors' first-generation Ambassadors were exported to Mexico in the first half of 1958 and assembled locally in the second half of the same year, and in 1959 by **Planta Reo de México** based in Monterrey, Nuevo León.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The model was restricted to the four-door hardtop sedan.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] It was powered by the four-barrel 327 cu in (5.4 L) V8 engine producing 270 hp (201 kW; 274 PS) coupled to a three-speed automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The model became the marque's top-of-the-line product alongside the three versions of the midsize Rambler and compact Rambler American models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] However, low sales figures alongside a deteriorating relationship between AMC and Planta REO led to the cancellation of the contract in the second half of 1959.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] American Motors again exported its products into Mexico with a new local partner, **Willys Mexicana**.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The agreement was signed in March 1960, and production began in Mexico City.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This meant discontinuing the Ambassador line in Mexico as the new operation had several priorities above offering a top-end luxury full-size car line.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Aside from marketing the already existing Jeep line, Willys Mexicana focused efforts on the compact Rambler American, which obtained a generation change the following year, meaning a complete retooling of the Vallejo plant.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] In 1962, legal and industrial requirements in the country became more assertive with the auto industry integration decree issued by the president Adolfo López Mateos in 1962.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Among its mandates, it entirely banned the importation of automobile engines.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Willys Mexicana began building its engine plant, which was achieved in November 1964.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Once the Rambler American was consolidated in the Mexican market, Willys Mexicana opted to expand the product line by introducing the brand-new second-generation Rambler Classic midsize model as a larger luxury counterpart to the economy compact American.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This resulted in the formation of **Vehiculos Automotores Mexicanos** (VAM).
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] After the corporate transition between 1960 and 1964 concluded, in which the Rambler marque under VAM surpassed the commercial results of its local predecessors Armadora Mexicana and Planta REO combined between 1950 and 1959, the company opted not to offer the Ambassador model.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The Mexican market of the era was still relatively small.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Since the Ambassador mainly shared the same styling as the contemporary midsize model, internal competition would affect the sales of a simultaneous Classic and Ambassador line-up.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Unlike the United States, with a larger and more diverse market for two different car lines with the same styling, AMC could differentiate the models with V8 engines for the Ambassador and the Classic limited to six-cylinder versions.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This advantage did not exist in Mexico since VAM could only produce six-cylinder engines in its Lerma plant, while V8 engines could not be imported from AMC because of the 1962 decree.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Instead, VAM opted to use the Rambler Classic as its most luxurious and flagship model, giving it the same treatment AMC put in the Ambassador model in the US and Canada.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] This would be passed on to the subsequent equivalent Rebel and Matador models produced under VAM.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] The 1958 and 1959 Ambassador models represent the only chapter in this model's history in Mexico.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] These were the only full-size American Motors products sold in the country, alongside the second generation 1974-1976 VAM Classic (Matador) models.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] It was also unique because it was a factory V8 model, the only AMC-based car marketed in Mexico with a V8 engine.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p02] Six-cylinder engines would power all subsequent models produced by the VAM.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] The Brampton Assembly Plant in Ontario, Canada, had been building Rambler and AMC vehicles since 1962, including the Rambler Ambassador until 1968.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] From 1969, Canadian-market Ambassadors were imported directly from the United States.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] The Brampton plant continued to assemble AMC vehicles through the 1970s and 1980s with the additional exceptions of Javelin, Matador, and Pacer, which were also otherwise imported.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] Ramblers were imported into Finland by two major Finnish automotive importers, **Oy Voimavaunu Ab** and **Suomen Maanvilelijäin Kauppa Oy** (SMK Group) during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] From 1962, the Rambler brand was advertised in Finland as an "American success car".
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] Available models included the Ambassador, Classic, and the compact American.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] From the mid-1960s, the **Wihuri Group**, a sizeable multi-sector family business, took over import operations using its shipping operation, **Autola Oy**.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] Wihuri continued to import small numbers of AMC vehicles until 1975.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] In 1969, American Motors did a deal with the Jaguar and Aston Martin importer for the Federal Republic of Germany, **Peter Lindner GmbH** in Frankfurt-Rödelheim.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] Peter Lindner became the distributor of AMC vehicles for West Germany, with the agreement to import seven AMC models including the AMC Ambassador.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] Peter Lindner continued to import AMC vehicles until 1977 after which German company Allrad Schmitt became the exclusive distributor for AMC passenger cars and Jeep.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] American Motors' vehicles were assembled in New Zealand by **VW Motors** in Auckland until 1962, and **Campbell Motor Industries** (CMI) in Thames, North Island from 1964.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] CMI assembled the Rambler Classic and Rebel models from knock-down kits and also imported fully assembled factory-right-hand-drive vehicles directly from AMC.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] Although neither firm locally assembled Ambassadors, twelve 1970 factory-right-hand-drive Ambassadors were believed to have been imported.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] These factory-right-hand-drive Ambassadors were built with the same dash, cluster, and instruments as the right-hand-drive Ambassadors previously built for the United States Postal Service in 1967.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] Ramblers were imported into Norway in the 1950s and 1960s by Norwegian firm **Kolberg Caspary Lautom AS** at Ås, Norway.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] KCL was formed in 1906 and imported automotive, industrial, and construction products.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] Three 1962 model year Ambassadors were brought to Norway in 1962.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] The Rambler Ambassador was imported by KCL in small numbers from 1963 until 1968.
[src:dodge-monaco/amc-ambassador-p03] KCL imported more significant numbers of the Rambler American, Classic, and Rebel during the same period.
